05136nam a22011295i 9780691218199DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211983nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912181997 a10.1515/97806912181992doi  a(DE-B1597)567590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a393/.094952231 aDanforth, Loring M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death Rituals of Rural Greece /cAlexander Tsiaras, Loring M. Danforth. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1983  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION: THE SELF AND THE OTHER -- t1. DEATH IN POTAMIA -- t2. THE ANTHROPOLOGY OF DEATH -- t3. DEATH AS PASSAGE -- t4. METAPHORS OF MEDIATION IN GREEK FUNERAL LAMENTS -- t5. WOUNDS THAT NEVER HEAL -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tPHOTOGRAPHS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis compelling text and dramatic photographic essay convey the emotional power of the death rituals of a small Greek village--the funeral, the singing of laments, the distribution of food, the daily visits to the graves, and especially the rite of exhumation. These rituals help Greek villagers face the universal paradox of mourning: how can the living sustain relationships with the dead and at the same time bring them to an end, in order to continue to live meaningfully as members of a community? That is the villagers' dilemma, and our own. Thirty-one moving photographs (reproduced in duotone to do justice to their great beauty) combine with vivid descriptions of the bereaved women of "Potamia" and with the words of the funeral laments to allow the reader an unusual emotional identification with the people of rural Greece as they struggle to integrate the experience of death into their daily lives. Loring M. Danforth's sensitive use of symbolic and structural analysis complements his discussion of the social context in which these rituals occur. He explores important themes in rural Greek life, such as the position of women, patterns of reciprocity and obligation, and the nature of social relations within the family.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxSocial aspectszGreece. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszGreece. 0aLamentszGreecexHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAlexiou, M.  aGod.  aHaros.  aaffines.  abinary oppositions.  abitterness.  ablack.  aburial.  acandles.  aclothes.  aconfinement.  acorpse.  adecomposition.  adeparture.  aearth.  aemergence.  aexhumation.  afamily relationships.  aflowers.  afuneral service.  agraves.  agrief.  aharvest.  aimmortality.  aincense.  ainheritance.  akerchief.  alaments.  alamps.  aliminality.  amarriage.  amemorial services.  amother-in-law.  anaming system.  aobligations of living to dead.  aommon-sense perspective.  apain.  aparadise.  areligious perspective.1 aTsiaras, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691218199zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691218199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691218199.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE